[Case 15 Round 2 Step 5] ENV: Bone Marrow:
                              Cytology: The aspirate smear was hypocellular for age (15%), showing markedly reduced trilineage hematopoiesis with dysplastic features in both erythroid and granulocytic lineages. Erythropoiesis displayed nuclear irregularities, multinuclearity, and occasional megaloblastoid forms. Granulopoiesis showed hypogranular myelocytes and pseudoвҖ“Pelger like neutrophils. Megakaryopoiesis was decreased, with a predominance of micromegakaryocytes and separated nuclei. Plasma cells were slightly increased, with a small atypical population (< 5%) showing eccentric nuclei, basophilic cytoplasm, and occasional perinuclear clearing. A focal blast component (around 5%) was present, composed of medium-sized cells with a high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, open chromatin, and indistinct nucleoli.
                              Flow cytometry: An expanded but small monotypic plasma-cell population (<1%) was identified, expressing CD38вҒә, CD138вҒә, cytoplasmic Оә light-chain restriction, aberrant CD56 positivity, and CD19 negativity. A blast population (4%) was detected, CD34вҒә, CD117вҒә, HLA-DRвҒә, CD13вҒә, CD33вҒә, and negative for lymphoid markers (CD3вҒ», CD19вҒ», CD4вҒ», CD8вҒ», CD20вҒ»), consistent with myelodysplastic-type blasts. The T-cell compartment showed a normal polytypic pattern, and the NK-cell fraction was preserved.
                              Histology: The trephine biopsy was hypocellular (15вҖ“20%) for age, with patchy hematopoietic activity and interstitial infiltration by atypical plasma cells (5%) showing irregular nuclei and mild atypia, arranged in small focal clusters. Trilineage hematopoiesis was markedly reduced, with dysplastic erythroid and myeloid maturation and decreased megakaryopoiesis with small, hypolobated forms. CD34 immunostaining highlighted scattered blast cells (5%) in focal groups. Reticulin staining revealed mild diffuse fibrosis (MF-1).
